Figure 1. Clinical and Radiographic Features of Necrotizing Enterocolitis Panel A shows an infant with a shiny, distended abdomen with periumbilical erythema. (Photograph courtesy of Dr. David Kays, Department of Pediatric Surgery, University of Florida.) In the radiograph shown in Panel B, the upper arrow points to portal air, and the lower arrow points to a ring of intramural gas, which is indicative of pneumatosis intestinalis. (Radiograph courtesy of Dr. Jonathan Williams, Department of Pediatric Pathology, University of Florida.) In Panel C, the arrow points to an area of necrotic bowel in a patient with necrotizing enterocolitis. (Photograph courtesy of Dr. David Kays, Department of Pediatric Surgery, University of Florida.)
